Ad Text:
Strategic Planning Manager – Scheduling

Location: Parramatta, NSW
Daily Rate: $480–$930 + super
Start Date: ASAP
End Date: 30/09/2026 (potential to extend)

We are seeking an experienced Strategic Planning Manager to lead and manage the development of integrated master schedules across large, multi-stream programs. This is an opportunity to shape portfolio delivery across complex ICT, ERP/SAP, or transformation initiatives.

What you’ll do:

Lead prioritisation and planning of the project pipeline to align with strategic goals and government priorities.
Develop and maintain integrated master schedules across multiple programs, projects, and workstreams.
Establish and embed scheduling best practices and control standards across the portfolio.
Facilitate dependency workshops, manage schedule-related risks, and provide scenario analysis for executive decision-making.
Support Program/Project Managers with schedule development, critical path analysis, and change impact assessments.
Collaborate with stakeholders and vendors to resolve scheduling conflicts and ensure governance compliance.
What we’re looking for:

Tertiary qualifications in Project Management, Information Systems, Engineering, or related field.
Formal training or certification in scheduling tools and methodologies (e.g., MSP Expert). PRINCE2, MSP, P3O, or SAP Activate desirable.
7+ years’ experience as a Master Scheduler or senior scheduling specialist on large, multi-year programs, ideally in government or ICT transformation.
Expertise in developing complex integrated master schedules, schedule risk analysis, dependency mapping, and critical path management.
Proficiency in Microsoft Project, enterprise scheduling tools (Altus desirable), PowerBI, and SharePoint.
Strong analytical skills, attention to detail, and the ability to communicate complex dependencies clearly to stakeholders.
Experience coordinating with vendors, agencies, and cross-functional teams.
Please note that only applicants with full Australian work rights will be considered.

The Company

A high-growth, ASX listed SaaS business with a global footprint based in Sydney CBD close to Wynyard.

Operating across more than a dozen international markets, the company combines the scale of a listed organisation with the pace and innovation of a modern SaaS platform. With multiple revenue streams, complex commercial models and continued expansion offshore, the finance team plays a critical role in driving insight, performance and strategic decision making.

The environment is fast moving, commercially sharp and highly collaborative. New products, new markets and evolving data points mean no two months look the same. It is a place where curious, resilient finance leaders genuinely thrive

The Role

This is a senior FP&A leadership role overseeing group forecasting, performance analysis and commercial insight across a diverse product and geographic portfolio.

You will lead a small team of analysts, partner directly with senior executives and shape the financial narrative that informs the board and wider business.

Key focus areas include:

End-to-end ownership of group forecasting across revenue, cost and headcount
Deep analysis of performance drivers, translating complex data into clear actions
Commercial partnering with product, technology, sales, marketing and HR
Oversight of multi-product, multi-market revenue models, including subscription, usage and payments
Supporting executive leadership with scenario modelling, strategic planning and investment decisions
Leading and developing analysts to lift capability, pace and commercial impact

This is a broad and influential role suited to someone who enjoys complexity, pace and genuine business partnering.

Your Profile

You bring strong experience from ASX listed or similarly complex environments, ideally with exposure to SaaS, subscription or usage-based revenue models. You're commercially curious, fast in your thinking and comfortable working in detail while keeping sight of the bigger picture.

You will thrive here if you:

Have operated at senior FP&A level with ownership of group-wide forecasting
Understand the dynamics of a listed business and what executive teams need from FP&A
Are confident reviewing and challenging models, assumptions and drivers
Enjoy solving problems in a fast-moving, evolving environment
Can work across functions and influence senior stakeholders with ease
Lead with clarity, pace and low ego, and enjoy coaching analysts

If you're an FP&A leader looking for a role that stretches you and puts you close to senior decision making, I'd be happy to share more in confidence.

Apply Today

The Opportunity

At APA, our purpose is to secure Australia's energy future. We're not doing it alone. We're doing it with our customers and communities as Australia's energy infrastructure partner, a role our unique experience and expertise positions us to play.

We have an exciting opportunity for a Senior Analyst - Gas West to join our Finance Energy Infrastructure Partnering team in Perth CBD office on a permanent full-time basis.

Reporting to the Finance Partnering Manager - Gas, you will play a critical part in supporting financial decision-making across APA's Gas Operations West business by providing meaningful insights, robust forecasting, and performance analysis. You will be embedded within the business to influence strategic priorities, lead planning and budgeting activities and support the development and delivery of business improvement and growth initiatives.

This is an ideal role for someone who thrives in a dynamic, data-driven environment and enjoys partnering with stakeholders to unlock value and drive better outcomes. The role presents a unique opportunity to join one of Australia's leading energy companies with a significant growth pipeline as it looks to secure Australia's energy future.

Key Responsibilities

Partner with a range of stakeholders at GM, Head of and Manager levels, present clear financial insights and support strategic business decisions.

Lead budgeting, forecasting, and long-term planning processes; challenge assumptions and provide insight on performance drivers.

Prepare monthly reports on financial performance with clear and insightful commentary, ensuring alignment with business strategic priorities.

Deliver meaningful financial analysis to identify trends, risks and opportunities across the asset and project portfolio.

Identify opportunities to streamline processes, improve data accuracy, and embed continuous improvement in financial workflows and systems.

Collaborate with other teams across the Finance division to gather data, obtain technical advice or share knowledge.

Your background

Strong experience in financial analysis, forecasting, and performance reporting within complex or asset-intensive organisations.

Advanced analytical and modelling skills, with experience using enterprise finance systems and tools (e.g., Adaptive Planning, PowerBI, Workday Finance).

Proven ability to drive budgeting and planning processes to completion within deadlines.

A continuous improvement mindset, always looking for ways to improve accuracy, reporting, and value creation.

Strong interpersonal and communication skills, with an ability to translate data into actionable insights; strong stakeholder management skills.

Relevant tertiary qualifications in Finance, Accounting, Economics or a related discipline; power and energy sector experience and knowledge perceived favourably.

Working at APA

At APA we're committed to fostering a safe and inclusive workplace where you can achieve your best. We'll provide you with access to targeted career development programs, competitive remuneration, employee benefits, flexible working arrangements, and wellbeing programs. We also have an inclusive parental leave policy providing 18 weeks leave including superannuation to support parents at work and in life.

We employ more than 2700 people across Australia and are committed to creating a diverse and inclusive culture, where everyone feels safe, valued, and trusted to do their best every day.

We are APA

APA Group is a leading Australian energy infrastructure business.

We proudly own, operate and manage a diverse $26 billion portfolio of gas, electricity, solar and wind assets which deliver essential services to communities and customers across Australia.

And we own more than 15,000 kilometres of gas pipelines which deliver energy to households and businesses across every corner of Australia.

As the partner of choice in delivering infrastructure solutions for the energy transition, we're focused on bundled remote grid energy solutions, electricity and gas transmission, and future energy, including hydrogen and carbon capture and storage.

Our customer centric approach means we understand our customers and offer them reliable, innovative, and cost-effective energy solutions that support their decarbonisation ambitions.

We are committed securing Australia's energy future by delivering infrastructure solutions for Australia's energy transition and supporting the decarbonisation ambitions of our customers and communities .

Join our team and be part of securing Australia's energy future.

We'd love to hear from you.

APA is an equal opportunity employer. The safety, health and wellbeing our people, community and environment a priority. We embrace diversity in our people to ensure our workforce is representative of the communities that we operate in.

About Us

The Borg Group is a leading privately-owned Australian enterprise with a strong presence in manufacturing, recycling, and property development. Founded in 1989 by brothers John and Michael Borg, the company is headquartered in Somersby, New South Wales, and employs nearly 3,000 people across Australia and New Zealand.

Borg is committed to environmental responsibility, actively integrating sustainable practices into its operations. Initiatives such as reDirect Recycling and Direct Pallets play a key role in reclaiming materials like used formwork, trusses, plywood, particleboard, and pallets. These efforts not only reduce landfill waste but also contribute to the production of recycled-content particleboard.

Innovation is a cornerstone of Borg’s success. The company continually invests in automation and advanced technologies, driving new product development and maintaining its position at the cutting edge of the industry. Its world-class manufacturing facilities are a testament to this forward-thinking approach. 

Borg’s diverse portfolio includes several prominent brands, notably polytec and Porta.

polytec is a renowned Australian brand offering decorative surface solutions for both residential and commercial interiors. It is a favourite among designers and renovators across the country for its style and quality.

Porta is a trusted supplier of premium timber and panel products for the construction industry. Known for its deep expertise and commitment to innovation, Porta delivers strength, quality, and reliability to every project.

For more insight into the Borg Group and what we do, please refer to our website www.borgs.com.au




About the Role

Our Technology Division plays a central role in driving digital transformation — integrating ERP systems, automation, data, and AI to support smarter decision-making and operational excellence.

As the Data & Analytics Manager, you’ll lead the development and governance of Borg’s enterprise data ecosystem.

You will play a pivotal role in designing and managing our Microsoft Fabric, Dataverse, and Power BI environments — ensuring the business has a trusted single source of truth for decision-making and innovation.

This is a hands-on leadership position, balancing strategy and execution, to enable Borg’s next generation of data-driven manufacturing and supply chain operations.

This position is located at our corporate head office at Somersby on the NSW Central Coast.

Key Responsibilities

Lead the architecture, implementation, and ongoing management of Microsoft Fabric, Dataverse, and OneLake platforms.

Build and maintain data models spanning ERP (D365), production, finance, and timekeeping systems.

Oversee data governance, including data quality, security, and lineage.

Manage the Power BI reporting ecosystem, transitioning from legacy ZAP reporting to modern, dynamic dashboards.

Partner with business stakeholders to deliver self-service analytics and actionable insights.

Collaborate with the Integration & Automation team to feed data pipelines for AI and machine learning use cases.

Mentor a small but growing team of Data Engineers, BI Developers, and Analysts.

Support the Head of Digital Solutions in shaping Borg’s enterprise data strategy.

About you

You’re an experienced data leader who thrives on building practical, modern data platforms that transform how organisations use information. You combine technical depth with a collaborative mindset and a passion for driving results.

Skills & Experience

Minimum 5+ years’ experience in data engineering, analytics, or business intelligence.

Strong proficiency in Microsoft Power BI, Azure Data Factory, SQL, DAX, and data modelling.

Exposure to or experience with Microsoft Fabric, Dataverse, or OneLake preferred.

Solid understanding of data governance, security, and quality frameworks.

Ability to translate business needs into technical solutions.

Excellent stakeholder engagement, influencing, and communication skills.

Experience managing or mentoring data teams is highly desirable.

 Why Join Borg 

Be part of a business that is investing in digital innovation and AI adoption.

Work within a collaborative, forward-looking Technology Division that partners closely with manufacturing, logistics, and operations teams.

Enjoy career growth opportunities in one of Australia’s most progressive manufacturing organisations.

Competitive salary package and professional development support.

• Developing and maintaining Defence-aligned finance governance artefacts

Team and environment

Who this role suits
Candidates with backgrounds in Defence finance teams, finance transformation, SAP finance, finance data governance, financial policy, government consulting or similar domains. Minimum of Baseline Security clearance is required for this role.

About the Business
A proudly Australian success story, my client is a private-equity backed organisation renowned for its manufacturing, innovation, and commitment to quality. The business is entering an exciting new phase of growth, underpinned by a significant capital investment — the development of a new, state-of-the-art manufacturing facility.

Monitoring and managing project expenditure against approved budgets, forecasts, and cash flow.

Provide high level technical and analytical expertise to initiatives of the Data and Analytics Branch.
Contribute to the design, build and implementation of reports, dashboards, analytic and data products that support business processes and deliver business insight.
Working with stakeholders to identify opportunities to leverage data and analytics to support consistent and efficient decision-making.
Influence business process and design to implement best practice information management and reporting principles.
Articulate complex information into simple messages that can be consumed by key stakeholders with varied levels of data literacy.
Contribute to best practice across the Data and Analytics Branch to ensure consistent analytics methodology and approach.
Mentor and lead junior analysts

What you'll need to succeed


Essential criteria

Significant experience in data analysis

Significant programming expertise (4+ years, SAS, SQL, R, Python)

Proven ability to deliver under limited supervision

Experience/strong familiarity with the use of data exploration and visualisation tools (e.g. PowerBI, Tableau, SAS Visual Analytics)

Experience working in an industrialised EDW environment.

Experience working within project management frameworks, the tools, and phases of the project lifecycle


Desirable criteria

Experience with SAS Enterprise Guide and/or Sas Viya

Experience mentoring junior analysts

Familiarity with Salesforce CRM and Analytics studio

Willingness to adapt to other analytics platforms and programming languages should the need arise


What you'll get in return


12-Month Contract

Hybrid Work Arrangements

Competitive Hourly Rates

Job Title: Senior Manager Risk Culture and Capability
Ad Text:
Step into a high-impact role where your vision shapes enterprise-wide risk capability, drives cultural change, and positions you as a trusted advisor to executive leadership.

Why join us?

You'll get 14% super as standard, to help your future come alive.
Unleash your potential and build a career to be proud of through excellent training and development opportunities.
Balance your work between in-person days at our purpose-built hubs and working from home.
In the office, enjoy end of trip facilities, a yoga and multi-faith room, parent and carer rooms, quiet rooms, BrewHub coffee facilities, and collaborative team spaces.

About the role

As the Senior Manager, Risk Culture & Capability at Australian Retirement Trust, you’ll be at the forefront of shaping and embedding a high-performing risk culture across the organisation. Reporting to the General Manager, you’ll lead the design and delivery of innovative frameworks and programs that drive strong risk behaviours, clear accountability, and uplift capability at every level. This is a high-impact, strategic role where you’ll partner with senior leaders, influence mindsets, and ensure ART not only meets but exceeds regulatory expectations. If you’re passionate about culture transformation and thrive in a dynamic, values-driven environment, this is your opportunity to make a lasting difference.




Key aspects of the role include:

Lead the development and implementation of ART’s enterprise-wide Risk Culture Strategy and Framework.
Design and deliver targeted risk capability uplift programs for leaders and staff.
Champion a values-aligned, transparent risk culture in partnership with executive and frontline leaders.
Conduct risk culture assessments using qualitative and quantitative methods.
Define and report on key risk culture metrics to senior leadership and Board committees.
Collaborate with People & Impact to embed risk capability into talent and leadership programs.
Act as a trusted advisor to the Chief Risk Officer and executive team on culture, governance, and accountability.
Ensure all initiatives align with APRA standards and regulatory expectations.
Build and lead a high-performing team of Risk Culture Specialists.
Drive continuous improvement through data-driven insights and stakeholder feedback.

This role is a permanent opportunity based in Brisbane, Sydney, or Melbourne

About you

It goes without saying you'll be a great communicator with top notch interpersonal skills. We'll also expect you to pick up problems and come up with quick, creative ways to solve them. It's quite likely you tick some of the following boxes too:  

Proven experience designing and delivering culture, leadership, or capability uplift initiatives in complex organisations.
Strong expertise in developing and using culture measurement tools, surveys, and behavioural diagnostics.
Demonstrated ability to lead and develop high-performing teams, fostering collaboration and professional growth.
Exceptional stakeholder engagement and influencing skills, with a track record of partnering with executive leaders and cross-functional teams.
Deep understanding of risk management principles, APRA prudential standards (especially SPS 220 and SPS 510), and regulatory expectations.
Advanced analytical skills with the ability to interpret complex data, identify trends, and provide actionable insights.
Outstanding written and verbal communication skills, including experience presenting to Boards and senior executives.
Strategic thinker with the ability to translate vision into practical, enterprise-wide implementation plans.
Experience collaborating with HR, L&D, and business leaders on people and culture strategies.
Relevant tertiary and/or post-graduate qualifications in risk management, organisational psychology, business, or a related field (highly regarded).

About us

Our 2.4 million members trust us to take care of over $330 billion in retirement savings. And we help them take charge of their finances and face the future with confidence. Our inclusive culture means you’ll be valued and heard in a respectful workplace. We've created an environment where you can be yourself and do amazing work. It's that simple.

Apply online now

Everyone is welcome to apply. We value diverse thinking, cultures, perspectives, backgrounds, and abilities. Awaken your career at Australian Retirement Trust and apply now. Applications close 7th December 2025.

We don’t want to leave you with a monstrous wait. So, you’ll hear from us after the closing date to find out whether you’ve made it through to the next round or not. Being fair and up-front is important to us – and recruitment is no different.

Ad Text:
Championing strategic clarity and innovation, you’ll shape the future of risk management by integrating cutting-edge technology, fostering collaboration, and delivering actionable insights that keep Australian Retirement Trust ahead of industry standards and regulatory expectations.

Why join us?

You'll get 14% super as standard, to help your future come alive.
Unleash your potential and build a career to be proud of through excellent training and development opportunities.

About the role

As Senior Manager, Risk Governance, Systems & Insights, you will play a pivotal leadership role in shaping the risk management landscape at Australian Retirement Trust. You’ll be responsible for designing, implementing, and continuously enhancing risk frameworks, systems, and enterprise reporting that support informed decision-making at the highest levels. This role requires deep expertise in governance, policy management, and risk technology, with a focus on delivering timely, high-quality insights to the Executive and Board. You’ll collaborate across all areas of the organisation to ensure governance clarity, policy consistency, and regulatory compliance under APRA’s prudential standards. If you’re passionate about driving strategic risk initiatives and uplifting governance maturity, this is your opportunity to make a significant impact.




Key aspects of the role include:

Lead the design, implementation, and ongoing enhancement of ART’s risk frameworks and governance structures.
Oversee enterprise risk reporting, delivering actionable insights to the Executive and Board Risk Committee.
Manage the risk management policy suite, ensuring alignment with regulatory and strategic changes.
Own the strategic direction and operational management of risk systems and technology platforms.
Coordinate system maintenance, upgrades, and enhancements for robust, user-friendly risk technology.
Standardise risk reporting templates and uplift reporting quality across risk domains.
Support regulatory reviews, internal audits, and policy development to meet APRA standards.
Foster collaboration across the organisation to enhance risk accountability and governance practices.
Build and lead a high-performing team of risk professionals, driving capability development and continuous improvement.
Monitor regulatory developments and act as a liaison for governance-related queries from regulators, auditors, and assurance providers.

Our Data Engineering Team is comprised of data experts. We build world-class data solutions and applications that power crucial business decisions throughout the organisation. We manage multiple analytical data models and pipelines across Atlassian, covering finance, growth, product analysis, customer analysis, sales and marketing, and so on. We maintain Atlassian's data lake that provide a unified way of analysing our customers, our products, our operations, and the interactions among them.

We're hiring a Senior Data Engineer, reporting to the Data Engineering Manager based in Sydney. Here, you'll enable a world-class engineering practice, drive the approach with which we use data, develop backend systems and data models to serve the needs of insights, and help build Atlassian's data-driven culture. You love thinking about the ways the business can consume data and then figuring out how to build it

Working at Atlassian

Atlassians can choose where they work – whether in an office, from home, or a combination of the two. That way, Atlassians have more control over supporting their family, personal goals, and other priorities. We can hire people in any country where we have a legal entity.

You'll partner with the product analytics and data scientist team to build the data solutions that allow them to obtain more insights from our data and use that to support important business decisions.

You'll work with different stakeholders to understand their needs and architect/build the data models, data acquisition/ingestion processes and data applications to address those requirements.

You'll add new sources, code business rules, and produce new metrics that support the product analysts and data scientists.

You'll be the data domain expert who understand all the nitty-gritty of our products.

You'll own a problem end-to-end. Requirements could be vague, and iterations will be rapid

You'll improve data quality by using & improving internal tools/frameworks to automatically detect DQ issues.

A BS in Computer Science or equivalent experience with 5+ years of professional experience as a Sr. Data Engineer or in a similar role.

Strong programming skills using Python

Working knowledge of relational databases and query authoring (SQL).

Experience designing data models for optimal storage and retrieval to meet product and business requirements.

Experience building scalable data pipelines using Spark (SparkSQL) with Airflow scheduler/executor framework or similar scheduling tools.

Experience working with AWS data services or similar Apache projects (Spark, Flink, Hive, and Kafka).

Understanding of Data Engineering tools/frameworks and standards to improve the productivity and quality of output for Data Engineers across the team.

Well versed in modern software development practices (Agile, TDD, CICD)

Benefits & Perks

Atlassian offers a wide range of perks and benefits designed to support you, your family and to help you engage with your local community. Our offerings include health and wellbeing resources, paid volunteer days, and so much more. To learn more, visit go.atlassian.com/perksandbenefits.

About Atlassian

At Atlassian, we're motivated by a common goal: to unleash the potential of every team. Our software products help teams all over the planet and our solutions are designed for all types of work. Team collaboration through our tools makes what may be impossible alone, possible together.

We believe that the unique contributions of all Atlassians create our success. To ensure that our products and culture continue to incorporate everyone's perspectives and experience, we never discriminate based on race, religion, national origin, gender identity or expression, sexual orientation, age, or marital, veteran, or disability status. All your information will be kept confidential according to EEO guidelines.

To provide you the best experience, we can support with accommodations or adjustments at any stage of the recruitment process. Simply inform our Recruitment team during your conversation with them.

To learn more about our culture and hiring process, visit go.atlassian.com/crh.
